arguments.prompt:
You are working on a Blazor Web App scaffolded at `/tmp/sv-fb5b7165f7f74353a20e3ca1ca22acff/ShipmentTracker/`. It was created with `dotnet new blazor -int Auto -au Individual` (net11.0). The solution has two projects:

- **ShipmentTracker** (server) — has EF Core with SQLite, ASP.NET Identity, server+WASM render modes
- **ShipmentTracker.Client** (WASM) — has auth deserialization, runs in browser

The Auto render mode means pages first render via Server (fast initial load), then switch to WebAssembly (no server round-trips). Individual accounts auth is already wired up.

## Requirements
- Dispatchers view a list of shipments with status and destination, and can update shipment status
- Customers check their shipment status and estimated delivery by tracking number
- Role-based authorization: "Dispatcher" role for staff, customers just need to be authenticated
- API endpoints for data access (since WASM can't access DbContext)
- Seed data so the app is usable immediately

## Implementation Plan

### 1. Shared Shipment model — in Client project (both projects reference it)

Create file `ShipmentTracker.Client/Models/ShipmentDto.cs`:
```csharp
namespace ShipmentTracker.Client.Models;

public class ShipmentDto
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string TrackingNumber { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Origin { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Destination { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Status { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public DateTime ShippedDate { get; set; }
    public DateTime? EstimatedDelivery { get; set; }
    public string CustomerEmail { get; set; } = string.Empty;
}

public class UpdateShipmentStatusRequest
{
    public string Status { get; set; } = string.Empty;
}
```

### 2. Shipment entity and DbContext — server project

Create file `ShipmentTracker/Data/Shipment.cs`:
```csharp
using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;

namespace ShipmentTracker.Data;

public class Shipment
{
    public int Id { get; set; }

    [MaxLength(20)]
    public string TrackingNumber { get; set; } = string.Empty;

    [MaxLength(100)]
    public string Origin { get; set; } = string.Empty;

    [MaxLength(100)]
    public string Destination { get; set; } = string.Empty;

    [MaxLength(30)]
    public string Status { get; set; } = "Processing";

    public DateTime ShippedDate { get; set; }
    public DateTime? EstimatedDelivery { get; set; }

    [MaxLength(256)]
    public string CustomerEmail { get; set; } = string.Empty;
}
```

Edit `ShipmentTracker/Data/ApplicationDbContext.cs` to add `DbSet<Shipment>`:
```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Identity.EntityFrameworkCore;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

namespace ShipmentTracker.Data;

public class ApplicationDbContext(DbContextOptions<ApplicationDbContext> options) : IdentityDbContext<ApplicationUser>(options)
{
    public DbSet<Shipment> Shipments => Set<Shipment>();
}
```

### 3. Add EF migration and seed data

After editing DbContext, run:
```bash
cd /tmp/sv-fb5b7165f7f74353a20e3ca1ca22acff/ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker
dotnet ef migrations add AddShipments
```

Then edit `Program.cs` to add seed data and role creation at startup. Add this BEFORE `app.Run()`:

```csharp
// Seed roles and sample data
using (var scope = app.Services.CreateScope())
{
    var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<ApplicationDbContext>();
    db.Database.Migrate();

